.\" Man page for exafs_action
.\" Format: groff man
.\" Installation: cp exafs_action.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/
.\"               gzip /usr/local/share/man/man1/exafs_action.1
.\"               mandb
.TH EXAFS_ACTION 1 "2025" "1.0" "fail2ban + ExaFS Integration"

.SH NAME
exafs_action \- fail2ban action to block IP addresses via ExaFS BGP RTBH

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B exafs_action.py
.B ban
.I <ip>
.I <bantime>
.RB [ \-\-dry\-run ]
.RB [ \-\-config
.IR file ]
.RB [ \-\-verbose ]
.PP
.B exafs_action.py
.B unban
.I <ip>
.RB [ \-\-dry\-run ]
.RB [ \-\-config
.IR file ]
.PP
.B exafs_action.py
.B list
.PP
.B exafs_action.py
.B \-\-help

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B exafs_action.py
is a Python script that integrates
.B fail2ban
with the
.BR ExaFS " web application (CESNET)."
It creates and removes BGP RTBH (Remotely Triggered Black Hole) rules
via the ExaFS REST API, blocking malicious traffic at the network level
rather than only locally on the host.
.PP
The script is intended to be called as a
.B fail2ban action plugin
(see the
.B CONFIGURATION
section), but it can also be run directly from the command line.

.SH ACTIONS
.TP
.B ban \fIip\fR \fIbantime\fR
Creates an RTBH rule in ExaFS for the specified IP address or network.
.I bantime
is the ban duration in seconds; it corresponds to the
.B bantime
value in the fail2ban configuration.
The rule is created in ExaFS with an expiry time of
.IR "now + bantime" .
.TP
.B unban \fIip\fR
Deletes the RTBH rule in ExaFS for the specified IP address.
The rule ID is read from the local storage file
.IR /var/lib/fail2ban/exafs/rules.json .
.TP
.B list
Prints all currently tracked bans (IP address and ExaFS rule ID)
from the local
.I rules.json
file. Does not require a connection to ExaFS.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-config " file"
Path to the configuration file.
Default:
.IR /etc/fail2ban/exafs.cfg .
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Simulates the action without actually calling the ExaFS API. Logs what
would be done. Useful for testing the configuration.
.TP
.B \-\-verbose
Enables detailed debug output (DEBUG log level).
.TP
.B \-h ", " \-\-help
Displays help and exits.

.SH INPUT FORMATS
The
.I ip
parameter accepts:
.RS
.PP
IPv4 address (e.g.
.IR 1.2.3.4 )
.PP
IPv4 network in CIDR notation (e.g.
.IR 10.0.0.0/24 )
.PP
IPv6 address (e.g.
.IR 2001:db8::1 )
.PP
IPv6 network in CIDR notation (e.g.
.IR 2001:db8::/32 )
.RE

.SH CONFIGURATION
The configuration file is in INI format and must contain an
.BR [exafs] " section:"

.RS
.nf
[exafs]
url            = https://exafs.example.com
api_key        = YOUR_API_KEY_HERE
community      = 1
whitelist_file = /etc/fail2ban/exafs-whitelist.conf
.fi
.RE
.PP
Default location:
.IR /etc/fail2ban/exafs.cfg .
.PP
The file should be protected from reading by other users:
.RS
.B chmod 600 /etc/fail2ban/exafs.cfg
.RE
.PP
.B Parameters:
.TP
.B url
ExaFS server URL without a trailing slash.
.TP
.B api_key
API key generated in ExaFS
.RB ( Administration " -> " "API keys" ).
.TP
.B community
Numeric ID of the RTBH community configured in ExaFS
.RB ( Administration " -> " Communities ).
.TP
.B whitelist_file
Path to the whitelist file (optional).
Default:
.IR /etc/fail2ban/exafs-whitelist.conf .
If the file does not exist, no whitelist is applied and all bans proceed normally.

.SH WHITELIST
The whitelist file lists IP addresses and networks that are
.B never
blocked via ExaFS RTBH, regardless of fail2ban decisions.
.PP
.B Format:
one entry per line, CIDR notation (IPv4 and IPv6).
Lines beginning with
.B #
and blank lines are ignored.
.PP
Example
.IR /etc/fail2ban/exafs-whitelist.conf :
.RS
.nf
# Internal management network
10.10.10.0/24

# Trusted monitoring server
203.0.113.10

# IPv6 documentation prefix
2001:db8::/32
.fi
.RE
.PP
The whitelist file is
.B hot-reloaded
on every ban action — changes take effect immediately without restarting fail2ban or the script.
.PP
The file should have restricted permissions:
.RS
.B chmod 600 /etc/fail2ban/exafs-whitelist.conf
.RE

.SH FAIL2BAN CONFIGURATION
Install
.B action.d/exafs.conf
to
.I /etc/fail2ban/action.d/exafs.conf
and enable the action in
.IR /etc/fail2ban/jail.local :
.RS
.nf
[sshd]
enabled  = true
action   = exafs
bantime  = 3600
.fi
.RE
.PP
To use a custom configuration file:
.RS
.nf
[sshd]
action = exafs[config=/etc/fail2ban/exafs-prod.cfg]
.fi
.RE

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/fail2ban/exafs.cfg
Configuration file (URL, API key, community ID, optional whitelist path).
.TP
.I /etc/fail2ban/exafs-whitelist.conf
Whitelist of IP addresses and networks that are never blocked.
Hot-reloaded on change without service restart.
.TP
.I /etc/fail2ban/action.d/exafs.conf
fail2ban action plugin.
.TP
.I /var/lib/fail2ban/exafs/token.json
Cached JWT token (managed automatically).
Permissions: 600.
.TP
.I /var/lib/fail2ban/exafs/rules.json
Map of IP addresses to ExaFS rule IDs (managed automatically).
.TP
.I /var/lib/fail2ban/exafs/rules.lock
File lock for concurrent access to rules.json.
.TP
.I /var/log/fail2ban-exafs.log
Action log file.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Ban an IPv4 address for 1 hour:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py ban 1.2.3.4 3600
.RE
.PP
Ban an IPv6 address for 24 hours:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py ban 2001:db8::1 86400
.RE
.PP
Ban an entire network:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py ban 10.0.0.0/24 3600
.RE
.PP
Remove a ban:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py unban 1.2.3.4
.RE
.PP
List active bans:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py list
.RE
.PP
Simulate a ban without calling the API:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py ban 1.2.3.4 3600 --dry-run
.RE
.PP
Use a custom configuration file:
.RS
.B exafs_action.py --config /etc/exafs-test.cfg ban 1.2.3.4 3600
.RE

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
The script logs to:
.IR /var/log/fail2ban-exafs.log ,
.B syslog
(via
.IR /dev/log )
and
.BR stderr .
.PP
On configuration error or ExaFS unavailability, the script exits with
return code
.B 1
and writes an error message to the log.
.PP
Retry behaviour: transient network errors and HTTP 5xx/429 responses are
retried up to 3 times with delays of 2, 4, and 8 seconds. An expired
JWT token (HTTP 401) triggers automatic token renewal and one further
attempt.

.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Error (bad configuration, ExaFS unreachable, retries exhausted).

.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.BR python3 " (>= 3.8)"
.TP
.BR requests " (>= 2.28.0)"
Install with:
.B pip3 install requests

.SH SECURITY
.PP
The JWT token is stored in
.I /var/lib/fail2ban/exafs/token.json
with permissions 600 (readable by root only).
.PP
The configuration file containing the API key should have permissions 600:
.RS
.B chmod 600 /etc/fail2ban/exafs.cfg
.RE
.PP
The API key is not passed as a command-line argument (which would make it
visible in
.BR ps " output),"
but is read from the configuration file.

